II. Advanced Segmentations¶

In this project, we want to introduce you to a new type of visualization that can be very useful, especially for classification tasks.

If you remember from the previous project, we introduced segmentations as a way to visualize the relationship between categorical and numeric features. We showed how you can use violin plots to show the distributions of some numeric feature segmented by a key categorical feature.

For example, for this dataset, we could segment 'satisfaction' by 'status' (the target variable) and see the relationship between satisfaction level and employment status.¶

  • These are called univariate segmentations because we are only displaying the distribution of one variable at a time after segmenting.
  • However, because the target variable is categorical, it can often be helpful to expand your segmentation analysis. (You'll do more of these in the exercises.)
In [3]:
sns.violinplot(y='status', x='satisfaction', data=df)
plt.show()
 
 

Now, right of the bat, we're gaining some useful information.¶

  • As expected, employees who are still employed are largely satisfied with their jobs, which is quite intuitive.
  • However, the satisfaction distribution for former employees who left the company is very surprising/interesting! The biggest thing that stands out is that it's not only unsatisfied employees who leave. In fact, there's a notable group of highly satisfied employees who have left!

Now, this alone is useful information, but there must be more to the story. Why is it that we're seeing a cluster of highly satisfied employees who are leaving? Well, one way to dig into this a bit further is to use bivariate segmentations to see whether there's another factor at play. Bivariate segmentations (in the way that we're using them) show you the relationship between two numeric features and a categorical one.

 

We can produce bivariate segmentations with the sns.lmplot() function from the Seaborn library.¶

  • sns.lmplot() is essentially a regular scatterplot with additional options.
  • For example, we can color each point based on its 'status'.
  • To do so, we'll use the hue= argument.
  • Note that we're setting scatter_kws={'alpha':0.1} to make the points partially transparent. We need to do this in order to see both classes.
In [4]:
# Scatterplot of satisfaction vs. last_evaluation
sns.lmplot(x='satisfaction',
           y='last_evaluation',
           hue='status',
           data=df,
           fit_reg=False,
           scatter_kws={'alpha':0.1})
plt.show()
 
 

This is a bivariate segmentation because we are plotting the relationship between two variables while segmenting classes using color. It's a quick way to see if there are potential interactions between different features.

Using the hue='status' argument is a quick way get this information, but sometimes this chart is too cluttered. Instead, it might be more helpful to plot a separate scatterplot just for those who've 'Left'.

To do so, we can plot another scatterplot of 'satisfaction' and 'last_evaluation', but only for employees who have 'Left'.¶

  • Note that we don't need the hue= argument.
  • Instead, we can filter the data=df argument.
In [5]:
# Scatterplot of satisfaction vs. last_evaluation, only those who have left
sns.lmplot(x='satisfaction',
           y='last_evaluation',
           data=df[df.status == 'Left'],
           fit_reg=False)
plt.show()
 
 

Nice... this is much clearer!

As you can see, it looks like there are indeed a few clusters of people who've left. While many machine learning algorithms can learn these automatically, sometimes it helps if we explicitly highlight these clusters.

So let's make a mental note to create 3 indicator features during feature engineering:¶

  • "Underperformers: for last_evaluation < 0.6
  • "Unhappy" for satisfaction_level < 0.2... maybe they are overqualified?
  • "Overachievers" last_evaluation > 0.8 and satisfaction > 0.7
 

III. Ad-Hoc Data Cleaning¶

In the previous project, we introduced the "rules" so to speak, in terms of the order in which you complete a machine learning project: Exploratory Analysis... then Data Cleaning... then Feature Engineering... then Algorithm Selection and Model Training.

Well, in this module, we're going to bend those "rules" a bit. You see, once you become very familiar with each of the moving pieces, you won't always need to keep a rigid order. For example, there are situations where doing a little bit of ad-hoc data cleaning can help your exploratory analysis.

While we would still recommend following the overall order of the framework, it's totally fine (and even correct) to do some light data cleaning and/or feature engineering while you're still in the exploratory analysis phase.

  • Tip: As a rule of thumb, however, we do not recommend saving the new dataframe from your exploratory analysis. To keep your project organized, we recommend repeating the dataframe-altering code in the actual Data Cleaning phase.
 

For example, based on the data dictionary (and the exploratory analysis you'll perform in the exercises), we can surmise that 'filed_complaint' and 'recently_promoted' should be indicator variables.¶

  • In other words, 1 should represent someone who filed a complaint / got recently promoted respectively, while 0 should represent someone who did not.
  • Instead, as we can see, the dataset has np.nan (i.e. missing values) where it should be the value 0.
In [6]:
print( df.filed_complaint.unique() )
print( df.recently_promoted.unique() )
 
[nan  1.]
[nan  1.]
 

This can be troublesome for us, even while we're performing exploratory analysis. For example, what if we wanted to calculate the correlation between recently promoted and satisfaction (maybe we want to see if recent promotions are correlated with higher satisfaction)?

Well, as it currently stands, we won't be able to calculate any correlations using those two features.¶

  • Notice the blank rows for 'filed_complaint' and 'recently_promoted'.
In [7]:
corr = df.corr()

sns.set_style('whitegrid')
plt.figure(figsize=(9,8))
sns.heatmap(corr,
            annot=True,
            cmap='RdBu_r',
            vmin=-1,
            vmax=1)
plt.show()
 
 

We can resolve this by fixing those features. They should be indicator variables, so let's fill their missing values with 0.¶

In [8]:
df.filed_complaint.fillna(0, inplace=True)
df.recently_promoted.fillna(0, inplace=True)
 

Now, we can re-calculate correlations successfully.¶

  • As it turns out, recent promotions do not appear to correlated with satisfaction level. (This could be good to know in case our HR team is thinking that giving more promotions is the solution.)
In [9]:
corr = df.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(9,8))
sns.heatmap(corr,
            annot=True,
            cmap='RdBu_r',
            vmin=-1,
            vmax=1)
plt.show()
 
 

IV. Ad-Hoc Feature Engineering¶

Similarly, we can also do some ad-hoc feature engineering to help us with our visualizations.

For example, you'll notice that one of our features, 'salary', is encoded as a categorical feature with 3 sequential levels.¶

In [10]:
print( df.salary.unique() )
 
['low' 'medium' 'high']
 

When a categorical feature's classes have a natural sequence, such as low -> medium -> high, this categorical feature is referred to as an ordinal feature.

As it turns out, we can choose to encode an ordinal feature using sequential numbers.¶

  • Again, this is because the classes have a clear order to them.
  • We would NOT be able to do this with the 'department' feature. Why?
In [11]:
df['salary_numeric'] = df.salary.replace({'low': 0, 'medium': 1, 'high': 2})
 

Thus, we've created a new, numerically-encoded version of the salary feature, where low salary is encoded as 0, medium salary is encoded as 1, and high salary is encoded as 2.

As a result, we can actually now calculate correlations between salary level and other numeric features, even though the original feature was categorical!¶

In [12]:
corr = df.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(9,8))
sns.heatmap(corr,
            annot=True,
            cmap='RdBu_r',
            vmin=-1,
            vmax=1)
plt.show()
